    <item>
      <title>Limited Invisibility</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/limited-invisibility/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 12 Aug 2022 16:41:02 -0700</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/limited-invisibility/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;body{color: #EEEEEE;}&#xA;img{margin-left: 5px;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: 5%;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class = &#34;centered&#34;&#xA;src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/LimitedInvisibility-web.jpg&#34; width=90%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div style=&#34;text-align: justify&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p style=&#34;text-align: center;&#34;&gt;&#xA;The Story&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The truck drove through the gate, and parked in a gravel parking lot between two windowless gray buildings. It was immediately surrounded by security guards. The driver got out and showed them her identification paperwork.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Back in the cargo compartment, where no one could see them, the passenger put on a special pair of boots and a vest covered with lenses and mirrors and complicated equipment. They flipped a switch&amp;mdash;and vanished.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Finding Yourself</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/finding-yourself/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 24 Jun 2022 17:22:13 -0700</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/finding-yourself/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;body{color: #EEEEEE;}&#xA;img{margin-left: 5px;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: 5%;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class = &#34;centered&#34;&#xA;src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/FindingYourself-web.jpg&#34; width=90%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Rahas stood in the makeshift laboratory, looking at the patterns on the oscilloscope screen.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Something&amp;rsquo;s not right&amp;hellip;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Something&amp;rsquo;s still wrong&amp;hellip;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m still not working properly&amp;hellip;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;They looked down at the switchboard on their chest. It was supposed to integrate the signals from the different parts of their mind, but it wasn&amp;rsquo;t. At least, not correctly.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Child Kit</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/child-kit/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 25 Jan 2022 18:09:03 -0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/child-kit/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;body{color: #EEEEEE;}&#xA;img{margin-left: 5px;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: 5%;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class = &#34;centered&#34;&#xA;src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/ChildKit-web.jpg&#34; width=90%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Sarah and Nathan had decided to build a child.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;ve cleared off the table,&amp;rdquo; Nathan said.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;OK, great.&amp;rdquo; Sarah set the down the big cardboard box, and they both started taking the brightly-colored plastic pieces out of it.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;At the bottom of the box, there was a tool kit and an instruction booklet&amp;mdash;fifty pages of semi-comprehensible cave drawings. Sarah looked at the first few pages, and started snapping together the main frame. This was the easier part&amp;mdash;things would be considerably more challenging when it came time to assemble the soul.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Roger and Deer 2</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/roger-and-deer-2/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 25 Jan 2022 17:48:02 -0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/roger-and-deer-2/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;body{color: #EEEEEE;}&#xA;img{margin-left: 5px;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: 0%;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class = &#34;centered&#34;&#xA;src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/RogerAndDeer2-web.jpg&#34; width=100%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It was a quiet Saturday evening. Roger was sitting in the armchair doing a Sudoku puzzle, and Deer was laying on the floor reading.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;There was a gentle buzz from the servos in one of Deer&amp;rsquo;s arms as he turned the page. He hadn&amp;rsquo;t used to read all that much&amp;mdash;his old robotic arm didn&amp;rsquo;t have the dexterity to turn pages or operate an e-reader, so Roger had included &amp;lsquo;ability to turn pages&amp;rsquo; in the design specs for the new ones.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Forest Pond</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/forest-pond/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 24 Jan 2022 13:59:39 -0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/forest-pond/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;body{color: #EEEEEE;}&#xA;img{margin-left: 5px;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: 2.5%;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/ForestPond-web.jpg&#34; width=95%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s a small pond in the center of the woods, with traces of a stone foundation nearby. A frog sits on a fallen tree. A few birds fly past.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;No humans have been here for a hundred years. The closest town is Rutherford Junction, sixty miles away at the edge of the wilderness. It&amp;rsquo;s not much of a town&amp;mdash;ten houses, a general store, one paved road, a tiny park, and a very small library.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Desert Gardens Expanded</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/desert-gardens-expanded/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 16 Jan 2021 09:48:00 -0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/desert-gardens-expanded/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;body{color: #EEEEEE;}&#xA;img{margin-left: 5px;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: auto;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;iframe class=&#34;centered&#34; style=&#34;border: 0; width: 100%; height: 42px;&#34; src=&#34;https://bandcamp.com/EmbeddedPlayer/album=2203451030/size=small/bgcol=ffffff/linkcol=0687f5/transparent=true/&#34; seamless&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://benconway.bandcamp.com/album/desert-gardens-expanded&#34;&gt;Desert Gardens (Expanded) by Ben Conway&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/DesertGardens_Expanded/City-web.jpg&#34; width=85%&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The Complex was near the center of the desert. The old concrete buildings were crumbling from decades of sand and harsh sun. Some of them were inhabited&amp;mdash;it was hard to tell which ones.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Sam looked out the window. A piece of trash blew past, and he saw one person walking down the street a few blocks away. That was it.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Unicorn Spacecraft</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/unicorn-spacecraft/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 27 Nov 2020 10:04:31 -0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/unicorn-spacecraft/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: auto;&#xA;margin-right: auto }&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;iframe style=&#34;border: 0; width: 100%; height: 42px;&#34; src=&#34;https://bandcamp.com/EmbeddedPlayer/track=1307406384/size=small/bgcol=ffffff/linkcol=0687f5/transparent=true/&#34; seamless&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://benconway.bandcamp.com/track/unicorn-spacecraft&#34;&gt;Unicorn Spacecraft by Ben Conway&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/UnicornSpacecraft/Cover-reworked-web.png&#34; width=900&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Sunlight is powerful. Whenever light shines on something, it creates pressure.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;And you can use that pressure to move a spacecraft.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The process of making a spacecraft begins with the unicorns. You can make a solar sail out of anything lightweight and reflective enough, but unicorn hair is the best material. We have six unicorns at our ranch&amp;mdash;Viduria, Sabelia, Sarustia, Aenarian, Salorsia, and Vidosion. There are a few different types of unicorn hair, graded by its coarseness&amp;mdash;different types are useful for different things. Salorsia&amp;rsquo;s a type D, for instance. You use that for structural support and reflective parts.&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Desert Gardens</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/desert-gardens/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 30 Oct 2020 13:06:28 -0700</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/desert-gardens/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: auto;&#xA;margin-right: auto }&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;iframe style=&#34;border: 0; width: 100%; height: 42px;&#34; src=&#34;https://bandcamp.com/EmbeddedPlayer/track=2800848693/size=small/bgcol=ffffff/linkcol=0687f5/transparent=true/&#34; seamless&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://benconway.bandcamp.com/track/desert-gardens&#34;&gt;Desert Gardens by Ben Conway&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/DesertGardens_1-web.png&#34; width=900&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;The desert was a barren expanse of sun-baked ground. About every fifteen miles there was a cluster of crumbling houses. It was hard to tell the abandoned houses from the inhabited ones.&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Near the middle of the desert there was a tiny pond. A few plants grew around it. Those were the only green things for miles.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Roger and Deer</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/roger-and-deer/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 25 Oct 2020 11:13:19 -0700</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/roger-and-deer/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;body{color: #EEEEEE;}&#xA;img{margin-left: 5px;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: -5%;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class = &#34;centered&#34;&#xA;src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/RogerAndDeer_web.png&#34; width=1000&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Roger was abruptly awakened by Deer&amp;rsquo;s loud electronic dance music, followed by the sound of his hooves as he walked out into the kitchen. Roger reached toward the nightstand to grab his earplugs, accidentally knocking his alarm clock to the floor and setting it off.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Great start to the day.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Chiron5</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/fiction/chiron5/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 18 Oct 2020 15:13:24 -0700</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/fiction/chiron5/</guid>
      <description>&lt;style type=&#34;text/css&#34; rel=&#34;stylesheet&#34;&gt;&#xA;body{background: #6E564A;}&#xA;IMG.centered {&#xA;display: block;&#xA;margin-left: auto;&#xA;margin-right: auto}&#xA;&lt;/style&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/Installment5/1-web.png&#34; width=800&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&#xA;&lt;br/&gt;&#xA;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/Installment5/2-web.png&#34; width=800&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;centered&#34; src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/img/Installment5/5-web.png&#34; width=800&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;We&amp;rsquo;re orbiting Kapteyn b. I&amp;rsquo;m looking at the photos coming in from the Chiron&amp;rsquo;s cameras and the orbiters we&amp;rsquo;ve released. Kapteyn b is a world of contrasts. The side facing Kapteyn&amp;rsquo;s Star is a sun-baked volcanic desert. The other side is a dark, frozen wasteland. In the middle, there&amp;rsquo;s a place where life can just barely survive.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
